## Pharmacokinetic and statistical analysis

The plot of plasma concentration (C) against time (t) data of metformin was carried out using Microsoft Excel 2010. The data were analysed to obtain pharmacokinetic parameters using the non-compartmental model by means of the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} Pharmacokinetic Software (United States). The results were recorded as mean ± standard deviation (SD). {{ drug.molecular_formula }}–10 h was computed using the linear method. The trapezoidal rule was applied when Cn > Cn−1. t0 was defined as C0. The AUCTwas estimated as the sum of {{ drug.molecular_formula }}–10 h. The {{ drug.molecular_formula }} h–∞. ke was the elimination rate constant and was obtained as the slope of linear regression of the ln transformed plasma concentration–time curve in the elimination phase. Half-life (t½) was computed from t½ = ln(2)/ke, clearance (CL) from Dose/{{ drug.molecular_formula }} and volume of distribution (Vd) from Vd = CL/ke = (t½ * CL)/0.693.

Comparisons of the pharmacokinetic parameters for the two products for determining BE were made using t-test and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} by means of the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} 16 Software. After transforming BA parameters (Cmax, {{ drug.molecular_formula }}–10 h, {{ drug.molecular_formula }}) to the logarithm scale, the data from both arms were compared by the 90% confidence intervals (CIs) using the ratio of geometric means. The test product was considered to be BE compared with the reference sample if the 90% CIs for {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and Cmax were within the predetermined BE range of 80% to 125% ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}, 2014).

Results

The innovator product and 13 generic brands of metformin were selected for preliminary quality appraisal screening by weight uniformity test, quantitative analysis and dissolution profiling. Twelve generic brands passed the weight uniformity test, while ten brands passed both the assay and dissolution tests, following the standard requirement stipulated by {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} as they contained between 95–105% of the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} of metformin and not less than 70% of {{ drug.molecular_formula }} dissolved within 45 min during in vitro dissolution ({{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}, 2007). Overall, nine generic products met all the standards stipulated in the official guidelines. The results for the assay and dissolution test are presented in Table 1 and Figure 2. Also, the quantity of metformin that went into {{ drug.dosage_form }} within 15 min is presented in Table 1, in order to show if the products rapidly dissolved to attain 85 % total release within 15 min with the aim of determining whether the products meet criteria for biowaiver. Though similar dissolution profiles were observed for all the products, except products C and K, only three generic products rapidly released ≥85% metformin {{ drug.molecular_formula }}. This led to the extension of this project to in vivo study.

